title: King Abdullah Park, Sea front

content: Umm Lajj One of the best beaches in Saudi Arabia It's one of the beautiful & cleanest beaches I have seen It was open for Public in 2015,nearing completion The beach is open and wide with small huts for public and swings for children. The water is clear but is a bit salty. The place is quite and clean There is not much around except for the beaches and hotels But it's a must visit for anyone on an enroute The city is serene and beautiful, population is not too much here & hardly any locals around . Beach is a relaxing spot perfect to visit in the evening . This beach will give you all an Instagram worthy shots. One of the drawback is that once you miss a u turn it will take kilometers to get the next one Expats are mostly around this beach There are also some sculptures on around the beach It's definitely worth visiting If u loved this review make sure to give it a big thumbs up. Peace

content: Extremely friendly people working in there!!! Not only is this place free of charge for visiting even by the tourists, but the staff offered us free bottled water while we were touring the place! I found the cutest souvenir shop in there! If you are into history and culture, make sure to take a slow tour around the castle and read the multiple signs and explanations in each and every room. There is also visual information, playing movies about the Saudi culture. Recommended with 2 hands!

content: The house of Nassif built by Omar Nassif is considered a landmark in Jeddah, where kings, princes, scholars, and ministers descended, so that the Ottoman Sultan Wahid al-Din was the last sultans of the Ottoman Empire after he was excluded from the caliphate, and the noble King Hussein bin Ali invited him to visit the Hejaz, and the princes of the holy city of Mecca came down to it then They turned into Muhanna Palace; King Hussein and his son Ali were also staying there. There was no hotel or guesthouse in Jeddah, except Nassif Palace, which is the hospitality palace for everyone who visited the Hijaz. In his six daughters and in Sheikh Muhammad Nasif, who is considered the grand heir of his grandfather; So the governor of the Ottoman grandmother, Ratib Pasha, made the palace a share of Muhammad Nasif because he is the only person able to receive guests, and after him King Faisal bin Abdulaziz purchased the palace from the heirs of Sheikh Muhammad Nasif in addition to the valuable library to make it the nucleus of public libraries in Jeddah. The ground floor of the palace contained the library, the table room, the rooms of the children, the guests, and friends, and there was a hostess attached to the palace, whose function was to receive the guests permanently, especially during the pilgrimage seasons. Abdel Azeez; He hurried to spend specific annual amounts to be paid each year.

title: King Abdullah Environmental Park

content: Nice historical site to visit if you are in the area. The wreckage is from the 60's. The fuselage is eroded with a separated tail segment and some missing part. This was a WWII surplus plane flown to the area by an American. The site is protected now but you can see graffiti on the some parts. The beach next to it is fantastic and you can see Egypt in the far distance (my phone actually connected to Egyptian cell network while here). Plan to explore the plane and have a picnic at the nearby beach. Bring sandals as the area around the plane floods with tide

content: Umm Lajj One of the best beaches in Saudi Arabia It's one of the beautiful & cleanest beaches I have seen It was open for Public in 2015,nearing completion The beach is open and wide with small huts for public and swings for children. The water is clear but is a bit salty. The place is quite and clean There is not much around except for the beaches and hotels But it's a must visit for anyone on an enroute The city is serene and beautiful, population is not too much here & hardly any locals around . Beach is a relaxing spot perfect to visit in the evening . This beach will give you all an Instagram worthy shots. One of the drawback is that once you miss a u turn it will take kilometers to get the next one Expats are mostly around this beach There are also some sculptures on around the beach It's definitely worth visiting If u loved this review make sure to give it a big thumbs up. Peace

title: Al-Qaryah Al-Turathiyah Restaurant

content: OMG! This park is so amazing.The lawns are lush green. Plenty of trees are seen everywhere in the park. Just in the front of entrance you will see a lake where colorful dancing fountains are installed but nowdays they are closed due to Covid. There are plenty of pole lights installed in the park so even at night one can enjoy awesome view of the park.The red colored train is a good attraction for both kids and adults. The ticket is very affordable, only 11 sr per head. On one side of the park there is a huge ground for outdoor sports like cycling, skating and kiting etc.Although there is a huge parking but still one faces problem in parking your vehicle. title: King Abdulaziz Center for World Culture - Ithra

content: The park is comprised of 4 kids play area, 2 prayer area separate for men and women and two separate restrooms. The park is best suited for families with kids and babies. There is a separate track for people who are interested in walking and jogging. The park is spacious and have more than two entrances. All the entrances supports wheelchair accessibility. There are four wheelchair accessible parking spaces reserved for people with disability. The slides here are in good condition but need maintenance. The park gets very crowded especially in the weekends. There are few local vendors in the park selling the goods for kids and babies. Covid19 prevention protocol: No body temperature is checked by the security at the park entrance. Masks are must to enter the premises of the park but no one is checking on this. No social distancing is maintained inside the park.

content: Al Masmak is a thick-walled fortress that was established in Riyadh during the second Saudi state time in the 19th century. It was built mainly for defense purposes, but later had different uses. After the fall of the second Saudi State, members of the Saudi royal family including, Abdulaziz ibn Saud (father of the current king), left Riyadh to live in Kuwait. Abdulaziz, who later baceme king, wanted to take back Riyadh from Ibn Rasheed. He had several attempts to recapture Riyadh but he did not succeed until his last attempt on an early morning of January 1902 (1319 AH). On that morning, Abdulaziz ibn Saud and his men reached Riyadh managed to recapture Riyadh from the chief of Riyadh at that time â€œibn Ajlanâ€ in a battle known today as The Battle Of Riyadh right at Al Masmak Fort. This battle was the starting point for re-unifying the different emirates and tribes of the arabian peninsula. which makes Al Masmak one of the most iconic places in Saudi Arabia's modern history. After the recapture of Riyadh; Al Masmak was used as a town hall and then served as a warehouse for munitions. What most people might not know about Al masmak is, that not too long after being used as a warehouse, the fort served as a prison until mid 20th century. Nowadays, Al-Masmak is a museum that covers the history of The kingdom with more focus on Riyadh and the battle of Riyadh. The museum contains artifacts, weapons, maps, a small theater showing the story of the Battle of Riyadh and a really good photo-gallery that gives visitors a brief insight of how life in Riyadh looked like in the first half of the 20th century. Al Masmak was built on top of a strong rocky foundation using local building substances such as clay, palm tree materials, straw, rocks and tamarix trunks. The fortress is one of few, well perserved mud buildings in Riyadh, which makes it a very good illustration of traditional najdi architecture. It is one of the kingdoms must visit museums and itâ€™s free Entry.

content: MARVELLOUS place for family. You will forget your all kind of problems for some times. Very nice place for kids, they can play and move here and there. Will get some natural moments. The place will remove your anxiety & tensions. Natural beauty is very nice. Different kind of flowers are bloomed everywhere to charm your mood. Especially the Fountain will fascinate you definitely. The lights of different colours on the streams of water of the fountain is like a synchronised dancing of beautiful ladies. It will give you much more joy. Coffee shop & snacks stores are available inside. Also have fast-food chain & brands Ice-cream parlours. It's a total package where you can spend quality time with your family.

content: This is my most favourite area of whole Riyadh! In fact I visited it twice during my 9-day-stay in the Saudi capital. It is really calm and picturesque. The weather was just lovely in the beginning of March. We had access only to this park and not to the other side of the historical part across the street. According to Google Maps there should have been multiple cafÃ© options around the Heritage park, but I didn't see any of those open. It is an amazing experience to be there at sunset! Highly recommended for both local people and tourists!!!!!

title: Green Mountain Resort

content: Qara Mountain is the perfect place to visit when you are seeking family adventure. On the outside, the view of the mountains are breathtaking. Then on the inside, there are many tunnels and exploring through them, was incredibly fun. Even though, they are open until midnight, I suggest to go in the morning because then, sun rays can seep through the small cracks of the mountain, lightly brightening up the caves resulting in some out of this world photos. The best part about Qara Mountain is the freedom you are given, there are no limits to your adventure and this made the trip unforgettable.

title: Al Mahmal Center

content: It would be 3 stars - since the pool is unavailable to women (for a Thursday night to Saturday checkout ) and the breakfast buffet is an incredible disappointment... however, the household and maintenance staff are wonderful. In order to get room service at 10:30 am on Saturday I had to call the front desk (room service and concierge phones were not answered). But the service was quick. It's a nice hotel.. some of the pros: bed and pillows are super comfy, very clean, lots of tv channel options for English and arabic speakers (French channels too), there are wonderful beachfront restaurants nearby, rooms with sea views are very nice). Additional cons: parking is overcrowded, 7th floor lounge level - friends paid an extra $250 per night for the same room with access to a "lounge" - they found no added value. Check-in took a long time.

title: Al Masmak Palace Museum

content: One of the best experiences I've had in South KSA (Jazan region). The valley of Wadi Lajab is a canyon about 5 kilometers long, situated about 80 kms away from Jizan city. The most incredible feature of Wadi Lajab is the fact that it delivers fresh water more regularly than any other wadi in Saudi Arabia. There is a stream that runs at the bottom of the canyon! It is believed that Majnu from the famous "Layla Majnu" (in which the hero Majnu bin Qais dies) came from Wadi Lajab region. Piece of advice: First, you can't come here if you dont have a 4 wheel drive because this is a mountainous rocky area. Arrange for a jeep or any other 4 wheel drive vehicle. Second, bring your own snacks and water, because there isn't any available for many kilometers. Lastly, make sure you wear good shoes so you can climb up rocks and keep a spare pair with you. It's even more fun if you come with a whole lot of people. YOU MUST VISIT THIS PLACE. THANK ME LATER.

title: Crowne Plaza Riyadh Minhal, an IHG Hotel

content: A very lovely green area. A large parameter to walk or run on the outside. Entrance fee is 12 SAR per adult. Not sure of the young fees though. Inside is a large green area suitable for a walk. Picnics are allowed. You can get your own food or buy from snack shops inside. The large lake showcases a dancing fountain every 1-2 hours after dusk. The times are a bit flexible.. so you'll have to wait to see. Kids play area is available with swings and slides. Though they'd enjoy running on the grass more. Down side is professional cameras are not allowed, which is a shame cuz its a lobely place to make memories. Yet you can take photos with your camera phone!!!

Ordered room service breakfast. Order arrived incorrectly, instant coffee in a pot for SAR20, the rest of the order was missed! Order was then corrected and arrived cold. My wife was not allowed to use the swimming pool, but was allowed to watch other (males) using it. Apart from that stay was ok. stay was ok

title: Awaliv Suites

content: One of the best five stars hotel in the city if not the best, we particularly liked the views from our deluxe room overlooking the marina. The room included breakfast which had various options ( e.g. omelettes, pancakes, pastries, cheeses and more ) to choose from. The hotel had various facilities like the swimming pool ( men only) and gym (separate ones, one for ladies and one for the gentlemen) Overall, customer service was great. The hotel management surprised us with sweets ( delegates tarts, macaroons and dates) every night of our stay. The hygiene level is on point, hand sanitizer everywhere and masks to stay safe from Covid-19. Our stay was memorable and will surely come back again

title: InterContinental Madinah-Dar Al Iman

content: At Dar Al Iman, the staff are very nice and supportive. They are cheerful and accommodating for guest needs. The hotel is adjacent to the Prophet Mosque which enabled me to devote more time for prayers. It is clean. Resturant's staff are very cooperative. Arrangements for breakfast and dinner are excellent, considering COVID situation. With the exception of the Welcome Amenity Points, Rewards Club members don't get more attention. During my previous stays (in 2019 and 2018) members were having breakfast at reserved locations. Also, they get discount for dinning at restaurants and cafe.
title: InterContinental Madinah-Dar Al Iman

content: Best and reasonable price to stay , very clean with big room and helpful/ cooperative staff , the food is very nice especially breakfast. They upgraded my room to suite because the AC is not working , they have good Parking. The problem is the location which is in very bad area but if you have car itâ€™s easy to go elsewhere in Riyadh. I recommended

title: Qasr Mall

content: More(Translated by Google) The Holy Kaaba, the Muslim kiss A lofty building in the heart of the Holy Mosque of Mecca, to which the hearts of Muslims yearn for it, and it is the first house placed on earth to worship God alone, without a partner. And the Kaaba is called due to its cubic, which is its square and every tall building (the Kaaba). Al-Nawawi said that it was called because of its roundness and height, and it was said that it was originally squared. The relationship is close and eternal between the Holy Kaaba since its construction and its near geographical surroundings, and by that we mean the Sacred Mosque, and this contiguity between them has led to a consideration of the increase in the areas of the Grand Mosque since the dawn of the dawn of prophethood, and it followed that in a way that allows Muslims to perform their rituals in reverence and reassurance. There was no mention of the Grand Mosque before Islam and it is known only to circumnavigate circling the Holy Kaaba, because the pre-Islamic era did not include prayers performed around the Kaaba, but they used to circumambulate around it only, and the ignorant people used to sit around it in the morning and evening, using it to shelter from the sun. And God guided Abraham, peace be upon him, to the location of the Holy Kaaba, and ordered him to build it, so he built it, and called again, and said: â€œLord, make this country safe.â€ Then he called in the third by saying: â€œSo make the hearts of the people that they like and provide them with fruits so that they may be grateful.â€ Various peoples lived in it, and the giants succeeded in governing the Kaaba, Jirhm, Khuza'a, Quraysh, and others. The Kaaba was the object of veneration and reverence for the people and the governors of Makkah, they reconstruct it and renew its structure when needed, clothe it, and regard it as a pride and honor for them, until Islam came and increased its honor, urged to venerate it and purify it, and the Prophet - may God bless him and grant him peace - and the Companions after him. content: We have stayed in Ascott Al Khobar for four nights in an executive city view suite. The overall rating for the experience would go 4 out of 5 due to the unavailable room services at this time. Everything else was excellent; the reception team was very supportive all the way. The housekeeping service was stunning. I had a personal situation that was handled very professionally by the hotel management. Thanks go to Lama for her proactive call, checking our satisfaction during our stay taking notes, and providing full support. I would recommend the hotel for long holidays.

Charger has fried zinger patty with lettuce, cheese and aioli, it was very tasty indeed and you can not compare it with any regular zinger burger at all! Jet Engine was juicy, includes grilled chicken patty, beef bacons(cooked properly), cheese, aioli and bbq sauce! It was the best i would say! And they gave us 2 extra sauces which were cherry on the top! Simply loved it!! For 39 SAR(including vat), totally worth the taste!

content: MoreThe best and beautiful place on the earth. Mecca is the birthplace of Muhammad. The Hira cave atop the Jabal al-Nur ("Mountain of Light") is just outside the city and is where Muslims believe the Quran was first revealed to Muhammad.[4] Visiting Mecca for the Hajj is an obligation upon all able Muslims. The Great Mosque of Mecca, known as the Masjid al-Haram, is home to the Ka'bah, believed by Muslims to have been built by Abraham and Ishmael, is one of Islam's holiest sites and the direction of prayer for all Muslims (qibla), cementing Mecca's significance in Islam.[5] Muslim rulers from in and around the region long tried to take the city and keep it in their control, and thus, much like most of the Hejaz region, the city has seen several regime changes. The city was finally conquered in the Saudi conquest of Hejaz by Ibn Saud and his allies in 1925. Since then, Mecca has seen a tremendous expansion in size and infrastructure, with newer, modern buildings such as the Abraj Al Bait, the world's fourth-tallest building and third-largest by floor area, towering over the Great Mosque. The Saudi government has also carried out the destruction of several historical structures and archaeological sites,[6] such as the Ajyad Fortress.[7][8][9] Non-Muslims (Kuffar) are strictly prohibited from entering the city.[10][11] Muslims from around the world visit the city, not only for the Hajj and Umrah pilgrimages, but also as tourists to visit regional landmarks such as the 'Aisha Mosque (Masjid 'Aisha) and the sites visited by pilgrims in the Hajj and 'Umrah. Mecca is now home to two of the most expensive buildings in the world, the Masjid al-Haram, valued at 100 billion US dollars, and the Abraj al-Bait complex, valued at 15 billion US dollars. Under the Saudi government, Mecca is governed by the Mecca Regional Municipality, a municipal council of 14 locally elected members headed by the mayor (called Amin in Arabic) appointed by the Saudi government. As of May 2015, the mayor of the city is Dr. Osama bin Fadhel Al-Barr.[12][13] The City of Mecca amanah, which constitutes Mecca and the surrounding region, is the capital of the Mecca Province, which includes the neighboring cities of Jeddah and Ta'if, even though Jeddah is considerably larger in population compared to Mecca. The Provincial Governor of the province from 16 May 2007 is Prince Khalid bin Faisal Al Saud.[14] Copy from Wikipedia

content: MoreMasjid Al-Ghamamah is one of the oldest mosques in Medina, Saudi Arabia, located in the place believed to be where the Prophet Muhammad ï·º performed an Eid prayer in the year 631. The mosque is one of the historical relics of Medina. The mosque was built during the reign of the Caliph Umar bin Abdul Aziz between the hijri calendar of 86 to 93 and later by many Muslim rulers. Masjid Al GhamÄmah is located northwest of the Prophets Mosque. It took its name after the clouds shaded the Prophet ï·ºâ€ while he was delivering his sermon. It was rebuilt at the time of the Ottoman Sultan, Abdul MajÄ«d in the year 1275 A.H./ 1859 A.D which is preserved until now. The Mosque is of a rectangular shape built with Black Basalt stones and roofed with 11 domes. The domes and walls are white on the inside whereas the pillars and arcs are black which gives Masjid Al GhamÄmah a unique appearance.

title: Crown Town Hotel

content: It was convenient stay, the check in and check out was normal. The room was good and spacious, with decent cleaning etc. Though furniture was bit too old and working table and associated chair were not optimum for work desk. I dream that one of these days the hotels will put adjustable height tables to meet modern day needs of business travelers. Two things were not good, 1) While room inside was neat and clean, the windows were really dirty, so you dare not to open the curtain. 2) Staff assigned to take body temp. was non serious and not doing his job, this means there is no real monitoring of temp. of visitors to the hotel. It was just a shame.

title: Jabal Omar Hyatt Regency Makkah

content: This is the worst experience I have had with this hotel. I have stayed here before but this is the by far the worst. I ordered room service for 4 people but received for 2 people despite having breakfast included for 4 people in my booking! The service is extremely poor, they downright REFUSE to serve us, whether housekeeping or in room dining! I understand this is 'in the middle of a pandemic' but that has absolutely NOTHING TO DO WITH SKIMPING ON QUALITY DESPITE CHARGING US ALMOST DOUBLE THE PRICE. I wanted to talk to higher up management, but the receptionist lady HUNG UP ON US MID-CONVERSATION. EXTREMELY RUDE. I AM EXTREMELY DISAPPOINTED, THIS IS ABSOLUTELY RIDICULOUS.
title: Jabal Omar Hyatt Regency Makkah

content: MoreQara Mountain is the perfect place to visit when you are seeking family adventure. On the outside, the view of the mountains are breathtaking. Then on the inside, there are many tunnels and exploring through them, was incredibly fun. Even though, they are open until midnight, I suggest to go in the morning because then, sun rays can seep through the small cracks of the mountain, lightly brightening up the caves resulting in some out of this world photos. The best part about Qara Mountain is the freedom you are given, there are no limits to your adventure and this made the trip unforgettable.

content: The overall experience is very nice. The hotel one of the best in Mekkah, the staff, location, and cleanness is excellent. I asked for a child bed and I got it almost imidiatlly. My only comments are: 1) the counter for check-in is not enough for the size of the hotel. 2) The procedure to get the car in the parking is complicated. I need to leave the car in the tunnel and go to check-in and then back to the car to take it to the parking. I prefer to go directly to the parking since I have a reservation number.

title: Hyatt Place Riyadh Al Sulaimania

content: The overall stay was great. However, it can be better considering the following comments; the reserved room was supposed to be with Haram view, however the view was very limited with partial view to haram. Also, one of the room windows was very dirty which was also another barrier to get the required view. The arrangement of the furniture including the bid and chairs can be better reorganized. The receptionists were requested to change the room with other one with better view with no luck. It is worth to mention that the hotel location is great and the room service including the restaurant and housekeeping were perfect.

content: Myconos restaurant in Jeddah ,KSA,was a very pleasant surprise for us. We have visited a lot of Greek restaurants,but most of the times,the food didn't remind us at all the really good taste of Genuine Greek Food. But in Myconos bistro was exactly the opposite!!!! We ate pantzari salat,manitaria Grevenwn, Trilogia,Sofrito, Mosharisia brizola,arnisio kotsi EVERYTHING EXCELLENT ,thanks of course to Greek Chef!!! Credits to the atmosphere also!!! The decoration,the music and of course the staff which were. Very polite !!!! So, Strongly recommended

During Eid, it may be visited by more than 41,000 people.[2] Sheikh Zayed Grand mosque Ø¬ÙØ§Ù…ÙØ¹ Ù±Ù„Ø´ÙÙ‘ÙŠÙ’Ø® Ø²ÙØ§ÙŠÙØ¯ Ù±Ù„Ù’ÙƒÙØ¨ÙÙŠÙ’Ø± ï¿¼ Sheikh Zayed Mosque as seen from the courtyard. ReligionAffiliationIslamBranch/traditionSunni Islam (Malikite)OwnershipGovernmentLocationLocationAbu Dhabi, U.A.E. ï¿¼ ï¿¼ Location in the United Arab Emirates Geographic coordinates24.412Â°N 54.474Â°EArchitectureArchitect(s)Yusef Abdelki of Halcrow Group[1]TypeMosqueGroundbreaking1996Completed20 December 2007Construction cost2 billion dirhams (US$545 million)SpecificationsCapacityover 41000Length420 m (1,380 ft)Width290 m (950 ft)Dome(s)82 domes of seven different sizesDome height (outer)85 m (279 ft)Dome dia. (outer)32.2 m (106 ft)Minaret(s)4Minaret height107 m (351 ft)WebsiteÙ…Ø±ÙƒØ² Ø¬Ø§Ù…Ø¹ Ø§Ù„Ø´ÙŠØ® Ø²Ø§ÙŠØ¯ Ø§Ù„ÙƒØ¨ÙŠØ± HistoryEdit The Grand Mosque was constructed between 1996 and 2007.[3] It was designed by Syrian architect Yousef Abdelky.[4] The building complex measures approximately 290 by 420 m (950 by 1,380 ft), covering an area of more than 12 hectares (30 acres), excluding exterior landscaping and vehicle parking. The main axis of the building is rotated about 11Â° south of true west, aligning it in the direction of the Kaaba in Mecca, Saudi Arabia. The project was launched by the late president of the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, who wanted to establish a structure that would unite the cultural diversity of the Islamic world with the historical and modern values of architecture and art.[5] In 2004, Sheikh Zayed died and was buried in the courtyard of the mosque. Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque Center (SZGMC) offices are located in the west minarets. SZGMC manages the day-to-day operations and serves as a center of learning and discovery through its educational cultural activities and visitor programs. The library, located in the northeast minaret, serves the community with classic books and publications addressing a range of Islamic subjects: sciences, civilization, calligraphy, the arts, and coins, including some rare publications dating back more than 200 years. The collection comprises material in a broad range of languages, including Arabic, English, French, Italian, Spanish, German, and Korean. For two years running, it was voted the world's second favorite landmark by TripAdvisor.[6] Design and constructionEdit The design of the Sheikh Zayed Mosque has been inspired by Persian, Mughal, and the Alexandrian Mosque of Abu al-Abbas al-Mursi Mosque in Egypt, also the Indo-Islamic mosque architecture, particularly the Badshahi Mosque in Lahore, Pakistan being direct influences. The dome layout and floorplan of the mosque was inspired by the Badshahi Mosque. Its archways are quintessentially Moorish, and its minarets classically Arab. Under lead contractor Impregilo (Italy), more than 3,000 workers and 38 sub-contracting companies were conscripted in its construction. The mosque was completed under a second contract by a Joint Venture between ACC and Six Construct (part of BESIX ) between 2004 and 2007.[7][8][9] Natural materials were chosen for much of its design and construction due to their long-lasting qualities, including marble stone, gold, semi-precious stones, crystals and ceramics. Artisans and materials came from many countries including India, Italy, Germany, Egypt, Turkey, Morocco, Pakistan, Malaysia, Iran, China, United Kingdom, New Zealand, North Macedonia and the UAE.[citation needed] Dimensions and statisticsEdit The mosque is large enough to accommodate over 40,000 worshippers, while the main prayer hall can hold over 7,000. There are two smaller prayer halls, with a capacity of 1,500 each, one of which is the women's prayer hall.[2] There are four minarets on the four corners of the courtyard which rise about 107 m

content: Although the food looks good, it doesnâ€™t taste as good. I expected much more for the price paid. the service was subpar and on the low end since I kept asking the waiters for things to bring and they just nod and ignore my requests. What makes this place different than other steak havens? Live cooking show! Sadly, I have visited this place multiple times for their cooking show options but everytime I visited I couldnâ€™t get such service either because the show chef isnâ€™t around or the show grill is undergoing â€œmaintenanceâ€ which is a bummer. The food is okay, not amazing but okay. Prices are shot through the roof for no apparent reason since I could get a similar steak at another restaurant for 20-30 riyals cheaper.

title: Hotel SwissÃ´tel Al Maqam - Tower F

content: The hotel is situated on strategic location. However, my experience in this hotel was very disappointing. The room was dusty and the carpet, bed linen, and towels are full of hair. The room service menu is limited and the quality of food was below average. At Your Service, the guest service center where you should inquire and place orders for housekeeping and in room dining, was not available most of the time, you have to dial the number for several times until someone picks up the phone, I've tried it in different timing and the result is almost the same every time. On the other hand, the team members that I have encountered with were in general polite, supportive, and friendly with minor exceptions. I guess, the hotel's management must go back to the basics in hospitality, and ensure that the rooms are clean, food quality is good, and service team is available to answer the phone. By the way, in my second week, I have received a call from the guest relations asking about my feedback about the hotel, and I've reported everything, but nothing has really changed, though, my stay at the hotel was a lengthy one and I had no other choice but to stay there for the whole period.

title: Riyadh Gallery Mall

content: MoreIt's was my first time during this Covid time. The arrangements were superb. Not very crowdy. Very systematic approach. You have to have a bus ticket, park your car at Kudai parking and get into the tent. Show your permit and they will give you a ticket to get in the bus. . Bus will take you to the Haram, it will dropped you off around 700 to 800 meters aways from Haram. Then you have to walk. Upon reaching at your authorized door guard will check your permit and let you through. Thermal cameras are installed for covid scanning. The way will take you straight to mataf. Mataf area is marked by various colors of tapes. Very convenient and easy to perform. After mataf pray two rakat sunnah and move to safa and marwa. Upon completion of Saii you will return back to your entrance door and move back to kudai bus station. Barber shops are open in clock tower building. Keep your Ticket with you. As it requires to show when you ride back. Bus then will take you back to kudai parking.
